    # [Scene: Saltwood Community Hall | Morning]

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fast, urgent strings under a mechanical pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of a crowded room; pages turning; distant gulls]
    "You wake with the taste of salt and paper at the back of your throat. Last night’s decision is a bruise under your ribs — accepted, tightened, signed in principle. The hybrid agreement sits now in"
    "other hands: lawyers' redlines, Dr. Elena Park’s precise edits, Mayor Hale’s pragmatic strokes. You accepted governance with teeth: legally binding environmental protections, guaranteed access points, a citizen advisory board with veto power on certain works. It"
    "was what you could bargain for and what many would call a compromise. You carry both the relief and the cost in the same breath."
    "You step into the hall and it narrows: faces that trusted you, faces that watched you hesitate, faces that will live with what you signed. Nyla is at the front, tablet angled like a shield, eyes"
    "rimmed red but steady. Aiden Koa stands by the far door, canvas jacket cinched, jaw set. Dr. Elena Park is across the table, hands folded, her anodized planner open like a promise — efficient, almost tender"
    "in its completeness, but the warmth is thin as the mist outside."

    "Mayor Jerome Hale raises his hands and the room quiets. Mayor Jerome Hale" "We have a binding memorandum and a funding schedule. We have timelines that will keep people safe and clauses to protect our marshes and access."

    "You move forward because you are still the hinge. Your voice finds the room as if it had been buttoned into place months ago. Maya Serrin" "The oversight clause is non-negotiable. If anyone signs on to work here, they sign it with us—not over us. The coastal engineering plans we accept will be adaptive. They will be reversible where possible. They will not block access to the quay. They will fund marsh restoration and a community trust for the next generations."

    "Dr. Elena Park's face is a careful mask; her amber eyes flick to the contract then to you. Dr. Elena Park" "Maya,' she says, slow and exact, 'we built our timelines around measurable outcomes. We can implement barriers in forty-five days and deploy automated gates before the wet season. That buys time while your marshes grow."

    "Aiden Koa steps forward before you can answer. His voice is taut. Aiden Koa" "And who pays if those barriers mean the fishing beds get cut off? Who pays for the nets that go empty because the current's been changed to feed your sensors?"

    "Dr. Elena Park meets him without flinching. Dr. Elena Park" "We included community access channels and compensatory ecosystem funds. We simulated displacement scenarios and have mitigation budgets."

    "Voice" "Paper doesn't feed the boys out there."

    "Nyla slides in at your side. Nyla" "We made the data public. We set the thresholds and the audit triggers. If metrics cross, citizen auditors can stop deployment until adjustments are made."
    "The dialogue tightens, trading facts and fears like knives. Every clause is argued three ways: technical, legal, human. You listen to the rhythm of it: Dr. Elena Park's precise cadence, Aiden Koa's rough interjections, Mayor Hale"
    "trying to translate both into something that will hold politically. Your pulse thunders in your ears — the VeryHigh pace the town has demanded of you for months condenses into this room."

    menu:
        "Talk the room through the oversight clause":
            "You take the binder, flip to the clause and walk the room through the enforcement steps, your fingers tracing the surveillance thresholds and community audit triggers. People nod, but their shoulders remain tight."
        "Let Nyla lead the technical demonstration":
            "You step back and watch Nyla pull up the live models on her tablet. Her voice races through timelines and fail-safes; her confidence is a thin bright wire that steadies the council for a moment."

    menu:
        "Stay with the rescue crews to stabilize the canal gates":
            "You knot your gloves tighter and lean into the physical work: hauling lines, patching a rupture with tarps and human muscle. You are bone-tired but present in every second."
        "Go with Nyla to triage the sensor data downstream":
            "You yank the tablet from Nyla's hands, eyeballs streaming graphs, re-prioritizing which neighborhoods get mobile pumps first. Your brain claws at numbers even as your chest caves."
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
